&gt;<br>
&gt;Much more then any of our probes could even hope to emit.<br>
<br>
 Anything under Europa's surface has several hundred meters of ice blocking any radiation.<br>
<br>
 The GNAWaNPiS site has a rant about this. It seems some jerk at NASA said something blithely about dropping a nuclear powered probe onto Europa, and just not worrying about letting it go.<br>
<br>
 Even I'll admit this sounds reckless, although I temper it, because Europa is a big place, and an RTG is really tiny.<br>
 They go too far, of course, and scream about banning all nuclear power in space.<br>
 It's a little difficult to recover an RTG powered probe from the bottom of Europa's oceans, so do we just use short-term battery powered probes? Do we design it so it leaves a thermal vent colony of life forms to go off into the distance to burrow under some mud to die, so it doesn't eventually leak right next to the life?<br>
 This still might be too much, and we can't guarantee that it won't die while it's sitting right next to a living thing near a vent.<br>
<br>
 The ideal is to build a big NPR powered ship from asteroid materials (place the asteroid mines with NPR upper stage rockets). Send out a water/chemical mine/colony to either an outer Jovian moon or a trojan asteroid, and send a nuclear powered sub to explore Europa.<br>
<br>
 40 years...<br>
 If Orion had been built when they first started, we might have that exploration ship/colony at Jupiter now. If we started sending asteroid mines out now, we might be there in 20. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#6F6F6F>- </font><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace>NuclearSpace Message Board</a><font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm12>Generic Space</a> <font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><a href="http://www.nuclearspace.net">NuclearSpace Home Page</a><font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 6.8<br>Copyright ©1999-2001 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  